value.value: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a chemical stimulus indicating the organism is under stress.

A DNA-binding ribonucleoprotein complex that contains a lncRNA complementary to the bound chromosomal locus and is involved in the tethering homologous chromosomes together during chromosome pairing at meiotic prophase I.
The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of macromolecules to form a protein-containing complex.
The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of proteins and DNA molecules to form a protein-DNA complex.
Any process that modulates a measurable attribute of any biological process, quality or function.

Any process that modulates a qualitative or quantitative trait of a biological quality. A biological quality is a measurable attribute of an organism or part of an organism, such as size, mass, shape, color, etc.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a molecular function, an elemental biological activity occurring at the molecular level, such as catalysis or binding.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of peptide bonds in a polypeptide chain by a mechanism in which the hydroxyl group of a threonine residue at the active center acts as a nucleophile.
An organelle lumen that is part of an intracellular organelle.
Binding to the D- or L-enantiomer of fructose, the ketohexose arabino-hex-2-ulose.
A protein complex in which at least one of the proteins is a cytochrome, i.e. a heme-containing protein involved in catalysis of redox reactions.
The covalent attachment and further modification of carbohydrate residues to a substrate molecule.

The process preceding formation of the peptide bond between the first two amino acids of a protein in a mitochondrion. This includes the formation of a complex of the ribosome, mRNA, and an initiation complex that contains the first aminoacyl-tRNA.
The successive addition of amino acid residues to a nascent polypeptide chain during protein biosynthesis in a mitochondrion.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA in a mitochondrion.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA in a mitochondrion.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA in a mitochondrion.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the process preceding formation of the peptide bond between the first two amino acids of a protein in a mitochondrion.

label.value: negative regulation of mitochondrial translational initiation

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the process preceding formation of the peptide bond between the first two amino acids of a protein in a mitochondrion.

label.value: positive regulation of mitochondrial translational initiation

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the process preceding formation of the peptide bond between the first two amino acids of a protein in a mitochondrion.

label.value: chromosome organization involved in meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A process of chromosome organization that is involved in a meiotic cell cycle.

label.value: protein localization to chromosome, telomeric region

value.value: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained at, the telomeric region of a chromosome.

label.value: regulation of establishment of protein localization

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the directed movement of a protein to a specific location.
Catalysis of the reaction: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) + a quinone = S0 (sulfane sulfur) + a hydroquinone.

definition.value: Note that EC:1.8.5.4 describes this reaction as bacterial-specific, but it has also been observed in eukaryotes (PMID:22852582, PMID:10224084).

value.value: Binding to phosphatidylinositol-4-phosphate, a derivative of phosphatidylinositol in which the inositol ring is phosphorylated at the 4' position.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) stimulus.

label.value: regulation of stress-activated protein kinase signaling cascade

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of signaling via a stress-activated protein kinase signaling cascade.

label.value: negative regulation of stress-activated protein kinase signaling cascade

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of signaling via the stress-activated protein kinase signaling cascade.

label.value: positive regulation of stress-activated protein kinase signaling cascade

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of signaling via the stress-activated protein kinase signaling cascade.
A cell cycle arrest process that results in arrest during G1 phase, whereupon the cell enters a specialized resting state known as G0 or quiescence.

label.value: G1 to G0 transition involved in cell differentiation

value.value: A cell cycle arrest process that results in arrest during G1 phase, whereupon the cell enters G0 phase, in the context of cell differentiation.

label.value: regulation of G0 to G1 transition

value.value: A cell cycle process that modulates the rate or extent of the transition from the G0 quiescent state to the G1 phase.

label.value: negative regulation of G0 to G1 transition

value.value: A cell cycle process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate or extent of the transition from the G0 quiescent state to the G1 phase.

label.value: positive regulation of G0 to G1 transition

value.value: A cell cycle process that activates or increases the rate or extent of the transition from the G0 quiescent state to the G1 phase.
Binding to a flap structure in DNA. A DNA flap structure is one in which a single-stranded length of DNA or RNA protrudes from a double-stranded DNA molecule.

A transport vesicle that mediates transport from an intracellular compartment to the plasma membrane, and fuses with the plasma membrane to release various cargo molecules, such as proteins or hormones, by exocytosis.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cold stimulus, a temperature stimulus below the optimal temperature for that organism.

label.value: positive regulation of ergosterol biosynthetic process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of ergosterol.

The protein complexes that form the electron transport system (the respiratory chain), associated with a cell membrane, usually the plasma membrane (in prokaryotes) or the inner mitochondrial membrane (on eukaryotes). The respiratory chain complexes transfer electrons from an electron donor to an electron acceptor and are associated with a proton pump to create a transmembrane electrochemical gradient.

A respiratory chain located in the plasma membrane of a cell; made up of the protein complexes that form the electron transport system (the respiratory chain), associated with the plasma membrane. The respiratory chain complexes transfer electrons from an electron donor to an electron acceptor and are associated with a proton pump to create a transmembrane electrochemical gradient.

label.value: exonucleolytic nuclear-transcribed mRNA catabolic process involved in deadenylation-independent decay

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of the transcript body of a nuclear-transcribed mRNA that occurs independent of deadenylation, but requires decapping followed by transcript decay.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus reflecting the presence, absence, or concentration of oxygen.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising microtubules and their associated proteins.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving tRNA threonylcarbamoyladenosine, a modified nucleoside found in some tRNA molecules.

A protein deubiquitination process in which a K63-linked ubiquitin chain, i.e. a polymer of ubiquitin formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 63 of the ubiquitin monomers, is removed from a protein.
Catalysis of the transfer of a cytidylyl group to an acceptor.
Catalysis of the transfer of an uridylyl group to an acceptor.
A process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a location within the mitochondrion.
A process in which a calcium ion is transported from one side of a membrane to the other by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

value.value: A cellular process that results in the biosynthesis of constituent macromolecules, assembly, and arrangement of constituent parts of a spore wall. A spore wall is the specialized cell wall lying outside the cell membrane of a spore.
